    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Valerius regum hostis, vt Brutus vndè Valeria Lex de prouocatione, et libertate populi. Qualis sacrata Iunia. Iunia de regio imperio: 
                        Lex Tribunitia. Leges Bruti, Valerij, Tribunorum, Tiberij, et Caij Gracchorum, aliorum popularium, valdè populares. 
                        Nerui plebis, et vincula popularis securitatis. Sed nihil violentum,</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Publius Valerius Publicola"/>
                    <person name="Lucius Junius Brutus"/>
                    <person name="Tiberius Gracchus"/>
                    <person name="Gaius Gracchus"/>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>diuturnu[m]: et Leges Romana[e] passim abrogantur legibus Romanis.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Valerius was the enemy of kings, so hence Brutus [instituted] the Valerian Law about the [right of] appeal and freedom of the people. 
                Of the same kind is the lex sacrata Junia. The Junian Law about royal authority; the Lex tribunicia. The laws of Brutus, Valerius, the Tribunes, of Tiberius and Caius Gracchus and of 
                others belonging to the popular party, were very much popularist. They were the force of the people, the ties of popular security. 
                But nothing forceful is permanent, and the Roman Laws were annulled everywhere in Roman laws.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Appellatio ad populum. Vnde status popularis: nec aristocratia iam, sed democratia.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Appeal to the people. From where the position of the people: not an aristocracy now, but a democracy.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Hoc agit: quicquid obtigit humanitùs.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>He took care of it, whatever occurred on a human level.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Nuper repullularunt homines, non tam literati, quàm feruidi, qui Monarchas froenare, et quasi castrari Reges voluerunt: 
                        ipsi nec maximi viri, nec optimi Politici. Quarum antesignani, novus Iunius Brutus, in Vindicijs contra tyrannos: Eusebius Cosmopolita, 
                        in suis Gallicis dialogis: Hotomanus Iurisconsultus in Francogallia: Buchananus in dialogo de iure regni apud Scotos: 
                        Dana[e]us in politicis aphorismis, nimis sa[e]pè ephorismis: Incertus scriptor de iure magistratuum in subditos; pla[e]riq[ue] tribuunt Beza[e]: 
                        et siqui tales. His autem omnibus affatim respondit Adamus Blacuoda[e]us Scotus, in Apologia pro regibus. 
                        Post Stephanum Gardinerum de vera obedientia: Laurentium Humfredu[m] de primatu regum, et magistratuum: 
                        multos tales regia[e] Maiestatis assertores, tam theologos, quam iuriscon. Nisi quòd magna etiam controuersia inter iurisconsultos Imperiales, 
                        et Pontificios; de qua alias accuratiùs.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Philippe de Mornay"/>
                    <person name="Nicolas Barnaud"/>
                    <person name="Francois Hotman"/>
                    <person name="George Buchanan"/>
                    <person name="Lambert Daneau"/>
                    <person name="Theodore Beza"/>
                    <person name="Adam Blackwood"/>
                    <person name="Stephen Gardiner"/>
                    <book title="Vindiciae contra tyrannos"/>
                    <book title="Dialogi ab Eusebio Philadelpho"/>
                    <book title="Franco-Gallia"/>
                    <book title="De jure regni"/>
                    <book title="Politicorum aphorismorum silva"/>
                    <book title="De iure magistratuum"/>
                    <book title="Apologia pro regibus"/>
                    <book title="De vera obedientia"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Recently they have sprouted again, men, not so much learned as fiery, who wanted to restrain monarchs and see Kings castrated as it were. 
                They themselves are neither the greatest men nor the best politicians. The leaders of these are: a new "Junius Brutus," in his 'Vindiciae contra tyrannos', 
                Eusebius Cosmopolita [Nicolas Barnaud] with his 'Gallici dialogi', the legal scholar Hotman in his 'Franco-Gallia', Buchanan in his 'Dialogus de iure regni apud 
                Scotos subditos', Daneau in his 'Politici aphorismi', all too often ephorian maxims, the unidentified author of 
                'De iure magistratuum in subditos' (which most attribute this to Beza), and a few similar authors. Yet to all these the Scot 'De iure magistratuum' 
                has responded sufficiently in his 'Apologia pro regibus', after Stephen Gardiner's 'De vera obedientia', Laurence Humfrey's 'De primatu regum, 
                et magistratuum', and many similar defenders of royal authority, theologians and legal scholars alike. 
                Except that there is also a great disagreement between imperial jurists and pontifical ones, about which elsewhere in more detail.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
